 societal fractures. Using a social ecology of resilience model, Addiction Recovery and Resilience is a yearslong ethnographic case study of a faith-based health organization with a focus on long-term recovery. It explores the organization's triumphs and missteps as it has worked to respond to the opioid crisis and improve the health of affiliates and the neighborhood for nearly twenty years. Addiction Recovery and Resilience concludes with best practices for individual, organizational, and community health and public policy at a time when nontraditional health care providers are increasingly important.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aAfrican AmericansxMedical carevCase studies. 0aAfrican AmericansxSubstance usevCase studies. 0aChurch and substance abusezUnited StatesvCase studies. 0aCommunity-based social serviceszUnited StatesvCase studies. 0aFaith-based human serviceszUnited StatesvCase studies. 0aMedical carexReligious aspectsxChristianityvCase studies. 0aSubstance abusexTreatmentxReligious aspectsxChristianityvCase studies. 4aAfrican American Studies : African American Studies. 4aCriminology : Criminology. 4aCultural Studies : Cultural Studies. 4aGeneral Interest : General Interest. 4aSociology : Sociology of Organization. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Sociology / Urban.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUNY Press eBook Package 2022z978311149185140uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978143848739740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781438487397423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781438487397/original  a978-3-11-149185-1  SUNY Press eBook Package 2022b2022  aGBV-deGruyter-alles